# UI Cleanups, Context-Aware Component Installer & Epic Game Launch Fix

Two workstreams: (1) UI polish in the Components/Graphics screens, (2) fix Epic Games launching errors.

## Proposed Changes

### GraphicsTab — Remove `+` button

#### [MODIFY] [GraphicsTab.kt](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/component/dialog/GraphicsTab.kt)

Remove the `action = { IconButton(...Add) }` blocks on **both** Bionic (lines 48-52) and non-Bionic (lines 96-100) `SettingsListDropdown` calls for Graphics Driver. The `+` here was a shortcut to install custom drivers — this belongs in Settings > Components > Drivers instead.

---

### ComponentsManagerDialog — Context-Aware `+` Button & Installed Drivers

#### [MODIFY] [ComponentsManagerDialog.kt](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/screen/settings/ComponentsManagerDialog.kt)

**1. Context-aware `+` button (header, lines 168-178):**
Currently the `+` always opens a generic `.wcp` file picker. Change it so:
- When `selectedComponent == DRIVER` → open the `.wcp` file picker (zip drivers)
- When `selectedComponent == DXVK` → open `.wcp` picker (DXVK packages)
- When `selectedComponent == VKD3D` → open `.wcp` picker (VKD3D packages)
- When `selectedComponent == WINE_PROTON` → open `.wcp` picker (Wine/Proton)
- When `selectedComponent == BOX64` → open `.wcp` picker (Box64)
- When `selectedComponent == WOWBOX64` → open `.wcp` picker (WowBox64)
- When `selectedComponent == FEXCORE` → open `.wcp` picker (FEXCore)

The file picker behavior is the same (`.wcp` install), but the tooltip on the `+` button now says the component name dynamically (e.g., "Install Driver", "Install DXVK").

**2. Add "Installed" filter chip to DriverContent (lines 563-601):**
Currently DriverContent only has `MTR` and [GN](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/screen/settings/ComponentsManagerDialog.kt#66-85) filter chips. Add a third chip [Installed](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/service/epic/EpicManager.kt#348-383) to the right of [GN](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/screen/settings/ComponentsManagerDialog.kt#66-85). When selected, show all installed drivers from `AdrenotoolsManager.enumerateInstalledDrivers()` instead of fetching from the remote URL.

---

### Epic Games Launch Fix

#### Wine Debug Log Analysis

The log shows the game `openttd.exe` (Epic app `a327fdb31e934dc2984c3b7b45b1ef0b`) being launched via:
```
winhandler.exe "A:\openttd.exe" -AUTH_LOGIN=unused -AUTH_PASSWORD=... -epicapp=... ...
```

The launch sequence completes: explorer.exe loads, winhandler.exe starts, all DLLs load correctly, Vulkan driver loads. But then:
```
X connection to :0 broken (explicit kill or server shutdown).
```

**Root cause:** The [getInstalledExe()](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/service/epic/EpicManager.kt#348-383) in [EpicManager.kt](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/service/epic/EpicManager.kt) sorts by path length (shortest first = line 372) which may pick a launcher/helper exe instead of the actual game binary. Additionally, it doesn't filter common non-game executables like redistributables, installers, launchers, etc.

#### [MODIFY] [EpicManager.kt](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/service/epic/EpicManager.kt)

Improve [getInstalledExe()](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/service/epic/EpicManager.kt#348-383):
- Add more exclusion filters for common non-game exes: [setup](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/screen/xserver/XServerScreen.kt#1900-2253), `unins`, `crash`, `redist`, `vcredist`, `directx`, `dxsetup`, `_CommonRedist`, `EasyAntiCheat`, `BattlEye`, `launcher`, `UE4PrereqSetup`
- Prefer exes in standard game binary locations: root, `Binaries/Win64/`, `bin/`, `game/`
- Use largest exe heuristic as a better signal (game binaries are typically the largest)
- Exclude `_CommonRedist` and `Engine/Binaries` subdirectories entirely

#### [MODIFY] [XServerScreen.kt](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/screen/xserver/XServerScreen.kt)

Fix Epic working directory calculation (line 2373):
```kotlin
val executableDir = game.installPath + "/" + relativePath.substringBeforeLast("/", "")
```
When `relativePath` has no `/` (exe is in root), this appends empty string + trailing `/`, creating a path like `/path/to/game/`. This should be fine but let's verify the trailing slash doesn't cause issues by trimming it. Also ensure the `exePath` is properly made relative even if [getInstalledExe](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/service/epic/EpicManager.kt#348-383) returns a path that doesn't exactly prefix-match `installPath`.

#### Amazon/GOG Verification

Review `GOGManager.getInstalledExe()` and the Amazon fuel.json + heuristic exe detection to ensure they have adequate filtering:
- GOG: Uses `goggame-*.info` manifest files — should be robust
- Amazon: Uses `fuel.json` manifest first, then largest-exe heuristic — already filters `unins`, [setup](file:///home/max/Build/GameNative-Performance/GameNative-Performance/app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/ui/screen/xserver/XServerScreen.kt#1900-2253), `crash`, which is good but should add the same comprehensive filtering

